[normal]8[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Written evidence from the London Cycling Campaign (CYS0071)[bold]              [bold]The London Cycling Campaign welcomes the opportunity to contribute to th
[normal]e Transport Select Committee’s follow up
[normal] inquiry into cycling. We share the committee’s concern at the tragic death of 6 people in 
[normal]just two weeks on London roads.
[normal] The continued growth of cycling in London and the UK must be accompanied, and assisted by, a reduction of road danger to cycle users 
[normal]and pedestrians
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Summary[bold]&#xa0;[bold]. 
[normal]London Cycling Campaign[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]T
[normal]he London Cycling Campaign is a charity 
[normal]with more than 4
[normal]0,000 supporters of who
[normal]m
[normal] 
[normal]12,000 
[normal]are full 
[normal]members. We 
[normal]speak up on behalf of
[normal] everyone who cycles, or want
[normal]s
[normal] to cycle, in Greater London. Our aim is for London to be a world
[normal] 
[normal]class cycling city. Founded in 1978, our organisation campaigns for every street in the city to be cycle
[normal] 
[normal]friendly so
[normal] that
[normal] millions more Londoners
[normal], whatever the
[normal]ir
[normal] age or ability,
[normal] can enjoy the benefits of cycling, helping to creat
[normal]e a cleaner, healthier and 
[normal]less 
[normal]congested capital.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]LCC, and its 33 local groups, regularly respond to planning consultations, inquiries into cycling and 
[normal]provide
[normal] informed input to 
[normal]policy making at both the local 
[normal]and London-wide-levels. Our input and lobbying work led to the comprehe
[normal]nsive revision of London’s cycling programmes now encapsulated in the Mayor’s Vision for Cycling in London. While the LCC would like to
[normal] see
[normal] a significant acceleration in the pace of implementation of the Mayor’s Vision
[normal], we recognise it
[normal] as a 
[normal]major step
[normal] towards improving cycling conditions in the capital.  
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]1.[bold] [bold]reducing road danger[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]1.1
[normal] 
[normal]Cycle journeys in London have increased by 176% on main roads in the past decade
[normal],
[normal] and cycle commuting by Hackney residents now accounts for more than 15% of journeys
[normal] –
[normal] doubling
[normal] in a decade.  
[normal]Yet even the capital, where cycle journeys 
[normal]now exceed 57
[normal]0,000 per day, 
[normal]still has a low o
[normal]verall share of cycling at a little more than 
[normal]2% of all journeys, well below cities like 
[normal]Berlin (
[normal]15
[normal]%) or Amsterdam (36%). 
[normal]The overall figure for
[normal] the UK
[normal] is
[normal] 2% - significantly below the potential rate. 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.2 
[normal]The key factor in deterring more people from cycling in the UK is road danger and perceived road danger. Recent surveys, both in London
[normal] 
[normal]and the UK, consistently show that a quarter, or more, o
[normal]f the population would like to cycle or cycle more often. 
[normal]S
[normal]urveys carried out for LCC and British Cycling show that the number one factor deterring people from cycling is fear of road danger. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3 
[normal]As the 
[normal]DfT
[normal] funded programme of Cycling Demonstration towns
[normal] has shown
[normal],
[normal] cycling offers an exceptionally cost effective investment in the transport sector. 
[normal]The Cycling Demonstration Towns showed a cost/benefit ratio of £2- £3.5 for every pound spent and this is described as a conservative 
[normal]estimate
[normal]. 
[normal]A cost
[normal]/
[normal]benefit s
[normal]tudy in Copenhagen (a city with high cycling levels) found that the total socio
[normal]-
[normal]economic cost of cycling (including travel time, health factors, pollution and congestion) 
[normal]was 0.60 DK
[normal] (Danish Krone
[normal]) per
[normal] kilometre compared to 3.74 DK per kilometre for cars
[normal]. 
[normal] Cyclist fatality rates in Holland and Denmark compared to distance travelled are half those in the UK. 
[normal]1.4 
[normal]The NICE (National Institute of Clinical Excellence) report on walking cycling, published in December 2012, makes clear that the health cost
[normal]s
[normal] of an inactive population are enormous and comparable to those of smoking.
[normal] 
[normal]1.5 
[normal]LCC led the Love London Go Dutch campaign in 2012 that secured 42,000 signatures asking the future Mayor to make our roads 
[normal]‘
[normal]as safe and inviting for cycling 
[normal]and walking as th
[normal]ose in Holland
[normal].’
[normal] The elected Mayor made a commitment to realise this pledge and his response has 
[normal]been his
[normal] Vision for 
[normal]Cycling
[normal] 
[normal]which commits to both significantly improved infrastructure and safer lorries.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2. POLITICAL LEADERSHIP[bold]&#xa0;[bold]2.1[bold] [bold]In common with the Tr[bold]ansport Committee[bold] LCC believes that [bold]political will, within Government and within Local Authorities, is the single most important fundamental and overarching factor that will deliver improved conditions for cycling in the UK, and[bold] [bold]unlock the huge latent [bold]demand there is for cycling as an everyday means of transport[bold]. That political will needs to be reflected in a clear national cycling strategy, backed by adequate resources and funding, which lead to its implementation at local level throughout the country.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2 
[normal]LCC 
[normal]shares the view expressed by the Transport Committee, in its 2012 recommendations on cycling
[normal], that
[normal] local authorities must work together 
[normal]with central Government 
[normal]to achieve improved cycling conditions and therefore we are seeking to secure the sup
[normal]port of all local council candidates in the 2014 local elections for cycle-friendly measures in 
[normal]London 
[normal]wards.
[normal] Our recommendations to candidates. 
[normal] These 
[normal]will follow six themes
[normal] all related to reducing road danger and removing barriers to cycling. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3 [bold]Space for Cycling 2014 : [bold]key themes[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]2.4 
[normal]A key element of the process 
[normal]of switching people from 
[normal]short 
[normal]car trips (half 
[normal]of which
[normal] are 
[normal]less than
[normal] 5
[normal] miles 
[normal]in the 
[normal]UK)
[normal] to walking and cycling 
[normal]is the re
[normal]versal of the policy followed in the 60’s of re-designing cities to enable high-speed motoring. 
[normal]I
[normal]f we are to 
[normal]achieve the levels of cycling across all demographi
[normal]c groups that are 
[normal]seen in the Netherlands
[normal] then motor traffic must be deprioritised in favour of cycling
[normal] and walking
[normal] most notably for urban, local journeys
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.5 
[normal]This is, at heart, a political rather than a technical matter. To fulfil the 
[normal]Government’s and Local 
[normal]Authorities’ declared
[normal] commitment to sustainable transport
[normal], and the numerous environmental, economic and health benefits that follow
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]cycling 
[normal](and walking) 
[normal]must be given 
[normal]priority in both time and 
[normal]space over motor traffic
[normal] in the UK’s u
[normal]rban spaces
[normal],
[normal] as 
[normal]it is in the Netherlands and Denmark.
[normal] In this context the Government must re-emphasise 
[normal]that the Traffic Management Act must be used to 
[normal]prioritise 
[normal]the movement of 
[normal]people
[normal], wherever possible by 
[normal]cycling and walking
[normal], 
[normal]ahead of 
[normal]the movement of 
[normal]motor vehicles
[normal].  
[normal]A lesson learned in London is that pre-occupation with 
[normal]maintaining or increasing
[normal] road capacity for cars can lead highway authorities to overlook, or discard, traffic schemes that can reduce road danger to vulnerable road users and serve to
[normal] encourage walking and cycling. 
