[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4[bold].  Cycling Infrastructure[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1 
[normal]A
[normal]ll urban road infrastructure impacts on the safety of cyclists. The main issues restraining more cycling in London and identified by Londoners 
[normal] are:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2[bold] [bold]Cycle Networks[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3 
[normal]It is evident from successful cycling countries that cycle routes need to build into a network to give people the confidence that they will reach their destination along cycle-friendly roads without encountering major barriers.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.4 
[normal]As the Dutch Design M
[normal]anual for Bic
[normal]ycle Traffic (CROW) makes clear
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]cycle networks 
[normal]must offer
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.5
[normal] 
[normal]UK cycle networks, whether in London or
[normal] elsewhere, invariably fall down 
[normal]on some or all of these principles
[normal].
[normal] The Mayor of London has announced that a network of ‘
[normal]Quietways
[normal]” across London and “Grid” of cycle-friendly streets in central London will build into a network. The quality of such
[normal] 
[normal]a network
[normal] must meet continental standards to give people the confidence to 
[normal]cycle. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.[bold]6[bold] [bold]Main road network[bold] cycle provision[bold] [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The level of provision for safe cycling on 
[normal]UK main
[normal] roads
[normal] remains inadequate.
[normal] London’s 
[normal]Mayor initiate
[normal]d
[normal] a review of major junctions
[normal], 
[normal]following previous
[normal] deaths,
[normal] in recognition of the problems across the capital
[normal]. 
[normal]Cycling infrastructure 
[normal]on main roads 
[normal]is either non-existent or seriously inconveniences cycle journeys
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]I
[normal]n some cases
[normal],
[normal] new infrastructure increases risk for cyclists as at recent work on 
[normal]Henley’s
[normal] Corner 
[normal](
[normal]A406
[normal])
[normal].
[normal] This problem is certainly not exclusive t
[normal]o London and must be addressed right across the 
[normal]country. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.7[bold] [bold]One Way Road System Removal[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]O
[normal]ne way road 
[normal]systems (
[normal]or 
[normal]gyratories
[normal]) remain one of the biggest barriers to 
[normal]both safety and 
[normal]increased cycle use
[normal].  Progress on removing the 
[normal]gyratories
[normal] that blight large parts 
[normal]of 
[normal]UK cities 
[normal]has been very slow.  A major programme of one way road system removal 
[normal]and the introduction of 
[normal]high grade provision for cycle users and walkers is overdue
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]4.8[bold] [bold]Filtered Permeability Measures [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Such schemes allow people on foot or on bikes access through locations where through motor traffic is blocked 
[normal](often by low cost bollards or a no entry sign) 
[normal]for amenity or traffic management reasons. The 
[normal]impetus for such s
[normal]chemes often come
[normal]s
[normal] from residents seeking to eliminate rat running. Permeability schemes such as those in De Beauvoir 
[normal]Town,
[normal] Hackney 
[normal]and Claremont
[normal] 
[normal]Square,
[normal] Islington, attract thousands of cyclists per day (
[normal]up to 1500 per hour - 
[normal]high even by Dutch standards
[normal]).
[normal] 
[normal]The virtual absence of moving motor vehicles means that collisions are unlikely. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]4.9[bold] [bold]Speed Reduction[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]In combination with measures such as filtered permeability, speed reduction can create pleasant cycling routes that attract more riders
[normal] as well as reducing collisions
[normal]. 
[normal]Following r
[normal]ecent changes
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]DfT
[normal] guidance allow
[normal]s
[normal] 20mph limits on main roads such as the 
[normal]TfL
[normal] network
[normal], under certain specified conditions
[normal].
[normal]4.10[bold] [bold]Cycle Superhighways[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The cycle superhighways 
[normal]In London 
[normal]have pro
[normal]vided very visible way marking 
[normal]but they have introduced only a limited number of safety improvements, as acknowledged by 
[normal]the
[normal] Mayor’s commitment to re-design them with far greater use of mode separation notably at junctions where most collisions occur. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Cy
[normal]cle superhighway 2 in East London is a sad case where six cyclists have 
[normal]died in 3 years
[normal]. LCC advised against implementation of this
[normal] highway as originally proposed and welcome
[normal]s
[normal] the Mayoral commitment to re-design it 
[normal]with protected cycle lanes and 
[normal]treated junctions.  
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.11[bold] [bold]Greenways[bold]C
[normal]ycle paths through Hyde Park and Green Park in central London are highly popular. 
[normal]Well designed
[normal] Greenway routes and links 
[normal]can make 
[normal]a significant impact on improving conditions for both walkers and cyclists. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.12[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Recommendations[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]5[bold]. [bold]Children &amp; Cycle Training[bold]&#xa0;[bold]5.1 
[normal]Cycling, which enables children to stay active
[normal] and healthy
[normal], 
[normal]needs to be 
[normal]incorporated
[normal] in
[normal]to
[normal] the educational system
[normal],
[normal] as it is in the Netherlands
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.2 
[normal]Incorporating an element of cycle training into the driving test would enable drivers to understand the on-road strategies of cycle users and help reduce the incidence of collisions.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]5.3 [bold]Recommendations[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]6[bold].[bold]  I[bold]mproving Street Design &amp; Management[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]6.1 
[normal]Dutch planners and engineers consider cycle and pedestrian traffic from the outset of any design process.  It is clear that this does not happen in much of the UK.
[normal] 
[normal]Consideration of 
[normal]‘people’ capacity rather than just motor vehicle capacity would lead to more people friendly planning.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.2 
[normal]Not all the transport modelling software used by 
[normal]TfL
[normal] and other Highway Authorities allows cycle flows as inputs or outputs. 
[normal]TfL’s
[normal] guidance suggests 
[normal]that junction capacity modelling is unreliable where cycle flows make up 20% 
[normal](no longer uncommon in London) 
[normal]of the traffic flow
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.3 
[normal]Safety audits must properly consider cycle users. 
[normal]We note
[normal], for example
[normal], that
[normal] 
[normal]TfL
[normal] guidelines for safety audits of road sc
[normal]hemes do not require auditors to have any detailed knowledge of cycling provision or London Cycle Design Standards
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.4 [bold]Recommendations[bold]&#xa0;[bold]5
