[normal]9[bold].  SPENDING PRIORITIES[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]9.1 
[normal]Cycle 
[normal]use in
[normal] the UK has increased in those towns and cities where funding
[normal] has been 
[normal]provided –
[normal] London and the 
[normal]Demonstration Cycle Towns 
[normal]are the obvious examples. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]9.2 
[normal]T
[normal]he 
[normal]Rod 
[normal]Eddington
[normal] report on Transport specifically 
[normal]highl
[normal]ighted that investment in cycl
[normal]ing offered 
[normal]particular 
[normal]value for money
[normal]: 
[normal]“Improving the attractiveness of walking and cycling, e.g. by creating 
[normal]or upgrading routes, can provide strong returns with wider BCRs (benefit cost ratios) sometimes over 10.”
[normal] 
[normal]Eddington’s
[normal] conclusion was that 
[normal]“some
[normal] of the best projects are small-scale, such as walking and 
[normal]cycling 
[normal].”
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]9.3 
[normal]We note that a 
[normal]DfT
[normal] estimate of the a
[normal]nnual costs of traffic delays, accidents
[normal],
[normal] poor air quality
[normal],
[normal] physical inactivity, greenhouse gas emissions and noise resulting from motor traffic in urban areas was put at £38 - £48 billion pounds
[normal].
